thes.dc:title: OFS Mapped Vocabulary Version FINAL_V3
thes.dc:description: Vocabulary for Parenting Domain for OpenFamilyServices which contains all 3 levels of terms, and contains definitions for Top Level Headings. Vocab is consistent with Spreadsheet version OFS_Vocab_Ver3. Terms equivalent to IPSV terms are deprecated and IPSV terms have been mapped into the OFS vocabulary using copy and paste with their equivalent OFS term deprecated.

term.termNote: This term refers services and information providers which focus on identifying anger-related emotional dysfunctions, and in helping people to control or reduce emotional feelings and the physiological arousal that anger causes.

For the purpose of the ISPP vocabulary, the category of Babies covers the period from birth to 12 months. It covers the processes and equipment needed to look after a baby, including feeding, health, development and social and emotional needs.

Behaviour is about actions, processes and agents to help resolve behavioural problems. The focus is on behavioural problems and manifestations of those problems such as crime, drug and alcohol addiction and misuse, anti-social behaviour.

Disability covers types of disability both mental and physical. This section includes the impact of disability on the life of a child or parent or both and the family. Also covers the types of services and support available.

This term refers to the psychological requirement that usually centres on such basic feelings as love, fear, anger, sorrow, anxiety, frustration, and depression and involves the understanding, empathy, and support of one person for another.

term.termNote: Over the past few years, schools have been extending the services they offer. Many now open up their facilities outside school hours for pupils, their families and the local community. So far, more than half of all schools in the country offer some extended services for the pupils, families and communities they serve. By 2010, the Government wants that to be all schools. Examples of services include Ofsted-registered childcare, breakfast clubs, after-school clubs and family learning.

term.termName: Families - being a parent or carer
term.termNote: This section covers all the different types of families including step families, multicultural families, single parent families, adoption and fostering. It also covers issues for families such as conflict, family life and values and the child within the family.

term.termNote: The governing body employs the school's staff and has primary responsibility for admission arrangements. The school's land and buildings are owned by the governing body or by a charitable foundation.

Hate crimes occur when a perpetrator targets a victim because of his or her perceived membership in a certain social group, usually defined by racial group, religion, sexual orientation, disability, ethnicity, nationality, age, gender, gender identity, or political affiliation. Here, the term refers to services aimed at supporting victims of hate crimes, the eradication of hate crimes in communities through the provision of information and the fostering of understanding.

Health primarily covers the health of the child, common childhood ailments and the impact of long term and serious health problems. It also includes topics such as healthy eating, healthy lifestyle and hygiene.

relation.termName: Families - being a parent or carer

term.termNote: This term refers to services providing information and advice concerning all aspects of safety in the home, including, for instance, advice on legal requirements, and how to avoid potentially threatening situations for both adults and children.
Inability to work, because of an illness or disability

Learning in a wider sense than schools. It includes pre-school learning, sixth form, further and higher education, students, alternatives to school, study skills and skills such as reading, writing and numeracy.

This category covers things for children to do with and without their parents. It includes outdoor and indoor activities, things to do in the holidays, things to do for free, and activities within the family home such as painting and drawing, and unstructured activities such as playing and structured activities such as sports.
Drugs intended for medical uses
This term refers to services and equipment designed to enhance or provide freedom of movement and travel for children and adults with disabilities which prevent them from being otherwise mobile.

The category of Finances covers all of the issues to do with money and families. It includes benefits, income, working issues, maternity and paternity pay. It includes areas that can be important to the family finances such as budget, making a will, savings.

term.termNote: This term refers to services which provide information, support and advice to parents on different styles of parenting, normally categorised as Permissive, Authoritarian and Assertive-Democratic.

Law and rights as applied to parenting and children. The category covers the rights of parents and children, the legal framework for divorce, separation and for children working. It also coves topics such as age limits for children being able to do things (such as working)

Positive activities refers to structured activities (e.g., sports and physical activities, attending clubs and societies, and volunteering activities) and unstructured activities (e.g., those which young people choose to engage in during their leisure time such as going to the cinema). Positive activities generally refers to young people aged from 13 to 19.

This category covers the key stages of pregnancy and maternity. Pregnancy is defined as the period from conception (including pre conception) to birth. Maternity is the early stages of caring for a baby

This part of the vocabulary is about relationship problems and the various different relationships

These services can include organised clubs bringing parents together with the aim of sharing experience and information, as well as services which, for instance, broker arrangements between individuals for the provision of childcare.

Teenagers is a specific age group and is defined here as people aged 13 – 19. It includes topics such as aspirations as well as issues and problems teenagers face such as drugs, alcohol, sex and sexuality, pregnancy, leaving school and starting work or higher education.

Toddlers are an age group which is a transition between babies and children. There are a number of specific areas relating to toddlers such as behaviour and groups. There will be some overlap with babies, for example, weaning and development, and with children.

This covers all aspects of travel; from transport to and from school to travelling abroad with children. It also includes specific topics such as safety in cars, children travelling on their own and passports and visas.

The governing body employ the school's staff, contribute towards capital costs and have primary responsibility for admission arrangements. The school's land and buildings are normally owned by a charitable foundation.
The LEA employs the school's staff and has primary responsibility for admission arrangements. The school's land and buildings are normally owned by a charitable trust.
This term refers to services which broker or which provide opportunities for young people to take part in unpaid work experience as part of their school or college curriculum.

This term refers to services which broker or which provide opportunities for young people to take part in short term (e.g., summer holiday) work which can be unpaid voluntary, or paid work, or placements with organisations operating overseas.
